WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:06.000
Hi, everyone. Thanks for tuning in to another edition of Data Science Workflows with Posit Team.

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:12.000
I'm Nick Pelican. I'm a Principal Solution Architect at Posit, and I'll be taking you through using Orbital,

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:19.000
specifically Orbital for Python, in conjunction with Snowflake to deploy your machine learning models.

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:23.000
Let's jump right in.

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:28.000
So first off, what is Orbital? And a lot of you might be asking the question,

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:34.000
seen the last data science workflow that I did back a couple of months ago.

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:38.000
You might be asking, why are you talking about this? You already talked about Orbital.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:46.000
We've introduced recently some really cool capabilities to Orbital, specifically in the Python world.

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:52.000
So what Orbital does, what Orbital specifically for Python does, is it enables you to run the predictions

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:57.000
of Scikit-learn pipelines directly within databases.

00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:02.000
The best way to think of this is, first off, use the tools you're familiar with.

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:07.000
Python users, we all know Skit-learn to train your models.

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:18.000
Then you use Orbital to convert those models into native Snowflake SQL and then deploy them on Snowflake.

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:23.000
So you might be asking yourself, why would I use Orbital? Well, a couple of different reasons.

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:28.000
Number one, it enables you to share your models really, really easily with anybody.

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:31.000
And we'll jump into this in just a little bit.

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:36.000
What Orbital lets you do is, again, because it's converting models into SQL,

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:39.000
it's putting them into a language that Snowflake can understand,

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:46.000
which means that you can leverage all the great parts about Snowflake, including Snowflake Compute,

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:53.000
all of Snowflake's tools around things like views, materialized views, scheduled jobs,

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:58.000
to take your models and actually put them into production.

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:05.000
It's as simple as, and I'll show you this in just a second, one click or one SQL statement.

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:10.000
And the second reason you might use Orbital is it makes your models really, really, really, really,

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:13.000
and I can't understate this enough, really fast.

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:21.000
Because it is converting them to SQL, again, because it's putting them into that language that Snowflake understands,

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:27.000
it makes the models blazingly fast. And you'll see that in just a little bit.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:31.000
So without further ado, let's jump into it.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:34.000
So first off, I'm going to go to Posit Workbench.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:39.000
And I'm actually using Posit Workbench running as a native app within Snowflake.

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:43.000
So if you have any questions about using Posit Workbench directly within Snowflake,

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:51.000
please reach out to us or check out some of our other material on our partnerships page about this really cool new capability.

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:59.000
You can run the Posit tools, including all of your favorite IDEs, directly within your Snowflake environment.

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:07.000
So now that I'm in Posit Workbench on Snowflake, let me jump into Positron.

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:10.000
If you haven't seen Positron yet, welcome.

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:14.000
We're super excited to be releasing Positron as general availability.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:18.000
Just came out a couple of weeks ago. It's been in public beta, though, for about a year.

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:21.000
It's our next generation IDE. We couldn't be more excited to release this to the public.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:25.000
If you've got any questions about it, please check out our website.

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:28.000
You can download it to your desktop there.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:36.000
Or if you're a Workbench user in the most current versions of Workbench, you can upgrade and Positron's right there for you.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:41.000
So now I'm in Positron running within Snowflake.

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:47.000
And let's get started with fitting a model. So first off, I'm going to connect to Snowflake.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:54.000
You'll notice because I'm using Posit Workbench in Snowflake, connection parameters, everything is just taken care of for me.

00:03:54.000 --> 00:04:01.000
I don't have to worry about username or password. It's just handled.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:06.000
So now that I'm connected to Snowflake, let me access my data.

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:13.000
So I'm going to use IBIS. If you're not familiar with IBIS, really cool project from the team behind Pandas.

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:19.000
What IBIS does is it basically lets you run Panda statements directly against a SQL database.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:23.000
Definitely encourage you to check it out.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:29.000
Let me connect IBIS to Snowflake. And throughout this demo, I'll be using the loan data data set.

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:33.000
If you're not familiar with that, it's super popular. It's up on Kaggle.

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:36.000
The loan data data set is from Lending Club.

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:49.000
It's a data set of roughly two-ish million loans all throughout the U.S., mostly personal loans.

00:04:49.000 --> 00:05:07.000
Let's connect and grab that data. Let's actually quickly just run a count and see how many rows we're working with.

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:13.000
So we've got about two and a quarter million rows here in our main data set.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:18.000
For these purposes of this demo, I'm going to want to say I'm going to want to filter that down a little bit.

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:24.000
I'm going to want to take a representative sample of that data set with just my columns of interest.

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:27.000
You can see I've already cheated here a little bit. I've already done my feature selection.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:35.000
If you're doing this yourself, you'd want to do your own exploratory data analysis and feature selection.

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:40.000
So I'm going to do a sample down to 0.003 of the data set.

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:49.000
That'll leave me with about 5 to about 10,000 rows on which to to fit my model.

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:58.000
Let's grab that sample. You can see I'm taking just a quick sample of the data just to see what it looks like.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:08.000
So I've got my columns of interest, interest rate, the term of the loan, BC util, which is total credit utilization,

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:13.000
BC open to buy, and all utilization, which is all credit utilization.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:22.000
So what I'm going to try and do in this model is actually for a given loan, predict its interest rate.

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:28.000
Next up, do what we're all used to. I'm going to split into my training and test data sets.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:35.000
Again, with that target column being interest rate.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:40.000
So next up, let's create a feature engineering and model fitting pipeline.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:45.000
So if you're not familiar with scikit-learn pipelines, what scikit-learn pipelines let you do,

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:52.000
I'm doing that right here, is combine preprocessing and model fitting steps.

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:58.000
So you don't have to worry. So basically what that does is it takes all of your feature engineering and model fitting and fits it all together.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:04.000
So it remains one continuous model object.

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:09.000
So for preprocessing, what I'm going to do here is let's say I'm a grab term.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:16.000
That's my only categorical variable. And I'll just one hot and code that.

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:24.000
And then for my numeric columns, I'm going to do some mean imputation on the missing data.

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:29.000
And then I'm going to scale the data as well. Again, I'm just using standard scikit-learn functions for this.

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:34.000
So simple imputer, ordinal encoder and standard scalar.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:40.000
And this remainder equals pass through means that all of the remaining columns on my data set are going to get passed through.

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:46.000
So specifically what that will refer to, you'll notice I brought in one column called ID.

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:57.000
This is just the idea alone. And that one, I just want to pass through this feature engineering step untouched.

00:07:57.000 --> 00:08:01.000
And next up to predict this, I'm just going to use a simple linear regression.

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:09.000
Orbital supports a ton of different models. Towards the end, we'll talk about some of the limitations on orbital as well.

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:17.000
But you can do things like linear regression, logistic regression, GLMs, tree based models.

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:28.000
There's a ton of different options out there to fit in whichever model you find works best for your specific problem or data set.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:35.000
So now that I've defined my pipeline, I'm going to fit it.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:40.000
You can see scikit-learn just returns a visual representation of my pipeline.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:52.000
I've got my ordinal encoder, imputer, scalar, and then again, it's passing through that ID column.

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:58.000
Next up, what I'll do is I'm actually going to use the Snowflake model registry to save my model.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:04.000
Snowflake provides their model registry. It's a great piece of functionality that lets you save models.

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:12.000
Again, for reasons like MLOps, for reasons like compliance, auditing.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:19.000
So what I'm going to do here is use Snowflake Snowpark package.

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:23.000
I'm going to connect to the registry.

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:33.000
And then Snowflake requires a model signature. Model signatures, of course, being what the model expects as input features.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:39.000
So I'll use my training data set as that model signature.

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:44.000
And then I'm going to log the model into my registry.

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:50.000
Let's run that.

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:58.000
This can take a little bit, but the really cool thing about this, again, is that I'm using common tooling with other teams.

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:02.000
So what I might be doing here, I might have a model that I'm fitting using Orbital.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:09.000
But again, I'm using it, I'm fitting it, and I'm fitting it and registering it in Snowflake's model registry,

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:18.000
which means that if another team that's fitting models in another language or another team that's fitting models not using Orbital,

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:21.000
all of our models are going to be contained within our Snowflake model registry.

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:25.000
So anyone who's curious about the models that are out there in the wild in my company,

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:34.000
and was curious about model performance can go into the Snowflake model registry and just see the entire inventory.

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:39.000
And now my model is logged with Snowflake.

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:48.000
So it's got a model name, I'm just calling this Orbital test, and I've got a model version indicator.

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:51.000
Let's jump into where Orbital comes in.

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:57.000
So what I'm going to do here is import the Orbital package.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:03.000
And then what I'm going to do is have Orbital parse that pipeline that I just fit.

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:06.000
And what I'm going to do is I'm going to give it that same model signature.

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:17.000
You can see I'm using Orbital ML types to give it the type that it should expect from each specific feature column.

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:25.000
Again, we've got our ID, term, bcutil, bcopenify, and all util columns right here.

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:29.000
So let's let Orbital parse that pipeline.

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:34.000
Let's take a look at what that pipeline, what that parsed representation of pipeline looks like.

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:36.000
This is what Orbital is doing under the hood.

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:46.000
It is taking my scikit-learn pipeline and parsing it into a logical representation that it can then convert to any number of downstream functionality.

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:49.000
And in this case, we're concerned with SQL.

00:11:49.000 --> 00:12:01.000
So you can see here all of the different pipeline steps that I just did previously.

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:05.000
Now let's turn that into SQL.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:12.000
So what I'm going to do is run Orbital ML export SQL and tell it what table I want to run against.

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:17.000
It's going to be that loan data table I used at the beginning.

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:19.000
I'm going to tell it what dialect to use.

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:21.000
Orbital can work on a bunch of different SQL dialects.

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:25.000
In this case, we're concerned with Snowflake.

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:28.000
I'm giving it again that fit pipeline.

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:29.000
And there it is.

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:36.000
There's my model converted within seconds with just a couple lines of code into SQL.

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:42.000
And if you look at the name in the SQL, you can actually see what Orbital is doing and how it's converting.

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:53.000
So what we've got is you can see that ordinal encoding of the term variable.

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:59.000
You can see the mean imputation happening.

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:01.000
You can see the scaling.

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:12.000
And then finally, when you go into towards the bottom of the SQL statement, you can actually see the model steps, the model itself happening.

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:17.000
So you can actually see the model coefficients.

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:22.000
Right there.

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:27.000
So now that we have that model fit converted into SQL, let's run some inference.

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:29.000
And let's use because it's SQL.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:31.000
Let's use Snowflake to run that inference.

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:38.000
Let's use all that compute power that Snowflake gives us to run that inference really, really quickly.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:41.000
So what I'm going to do is I'm just going to use pandas.

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:48.000
Pandas read SQL, feed it that SQL along with my Snowflake connection.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:55.000
And let's see how fast that runs.

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:59.000
You can see that took about four seconds.

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:08.000
And those are, again, some predictions back directly from that entire large data set that's in my Snowflake environment.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:12.000
And let's see how many predictions just happened.

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:15.000
That was the entire data set.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:19.000
We just ran a model predictions over our entire data set.

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:25.000
Two and a quarter million rows in less than five seconds.

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:38.000
But then again, as I mentioned at the beginning, one of the really cool things about Orbital is that instead of having to deploy models, instead of having to figure out our Python run times, Docker images to deploy your models.

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:48.000
What you can do now is because it's native SQL, you can actually deploy this model to Snowflake as a native Snowflake object.

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:53.000
So what I'm going to do here is take that same SQL I used before.

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:58.000
Stick a create or replace view statement in front of it.

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:01.000
So what I'm creating here is a Snowflake view.

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:03.000
A Snowflake view is just a save SQL query.

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:07.000
Every time you run it, you can select from it as if it was a table.

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:10.000
It'll run that SQL query every time.

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:14.000
So I'm sticking a create or replace view in front of that SQL that I've already created.

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:17.000
I'm going to name it my model name.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:25.000
And then again, that version name I got from the Snowflake model registry.

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:30.000
So let's save that to Snowflake.

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:33.000
And now my model is deployed to Snowflake.

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:37.000
So let's take a look at what that looks like.

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:40.000
Let me copy that model reference.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:46.000
Let me jump into my Snowflake instance.

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:50.000
So now I'm in my in my Snowflake instance itself.

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:54.000
This is Snow site, Snowflake SQL dashboard.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:57.000
I've got a query here that I already wrote.

00:15:57.000 --> 00:16:06.000
Let me change this to reference the model that I just wrote.

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:12.000
So now what I have is what I'm going to do here is select ID, term, loan amount,

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:18.000
and my predicted interest rate from that model that I just fit.

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:25.000
Again, I'm using that view that I just saved to do the actual model inference.

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:27.000
And let's see how fast this runs.

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:30.000
Again, just while I'm doing this, keep in mind,

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:33.000
I'm not using some massive Snowflake compute engine here.

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:42.000
I'm using Snowflake's second smallest warehouse set to do all this work.

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:44.000
And there's my results back.

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:48.000
Takes only about took only about 1.6 seconds.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:52.000
It's that fast.

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:55.000
And let's compare that to doing the same thing,

00:16:55.000 --> 00:17:01.000
but using Snowflake's native Python runtime called Snowpark.

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:04.000
So here's the same query that I just ran,

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:07.000
but because I've saved that model in the Snowflake model registry,

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:13.000
I can use Snowpark to access it.

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:38.000
And let's run this and see how fast this runs.

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:45.000
You'll see that took around an order of magnitude longer to run.

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:48.000
So you might be asking right now, why is Orbital so fast?

00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:50.000
Well, a combination of different things.

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:54.000
Number one, Snowflake is really good at understanding SQL code.

00:17:54.000 --> 00:18:00.000
Snowflake on the back end translates SQL code into really optimized C code.

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:03.000
That's why Snowflake warehouses are so fast.

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:07.000
Because Orbital translates a model into something that Snowflake natively understands,

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:10.000
it's going to be that much faster.

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:19.000
The other reason is because if we go look at the query history,

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:27.000
let's take a look and compare and contrast these two queries.

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:31.000
So what you'll see happening here is this is the query that I that I ran first.

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:35.000
This is using my Orbital converted model.

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:39.000
This is using Snowflake because this is Snowflake native SQL.

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:42.000
Snowflake's query optimizer can work on it.

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:48.000
So it can do things like you'll notice instead of running on all two and a quarter million rows on this table,

00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:57.000
instead it's only running on, in some cases, 80,000, 51,000, 45,000.

00:18:57.000 --> 00:19:02.000
Instead, it's running on only a subset of rows because I had some filter statements in my query.

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:09.000
So that query optimizer is doing a lot of legwork, making sure this returns really quickly.

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:20.000
Let's go back and check out the other one.

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:22.000
And you'll see.

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:27.000
One of the other things that you that you don't have to deal with is for every time Snowflake is running Python,

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:29.000
it has to spin up a Python.

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:32.000
So you pay a little bit of tax with that.

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:36.000
So you'll see this initialization penalty happening.

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:39.000
That took up about 45 percent of the time.

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:43.000
Because if you convert a model SQL, Snowflake doesn't have to do that.

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:49.000
It's going to run that much faster.

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:52.000
Let's jump into some of the things that.

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:56.000
Orbital can do that Snowflake so that Orbital can do and Orbital can't do.

00:19:56.000 --> 00:19:59.000
So you might be thinking to yourself, this is awesome.

00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:01.000
I want to use Orbital for everything.

00:20:01.000 --> 00:20:07.000
Orbital is a fantastic capability, although because it is converting the SQL, there are a few limitations.

00:20:07.000 --> 00:20:14.000
As I mentioned, Orbital has a ton of capability to convert different models, convert linear regressions,

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:18.000
logistic regressions, tree based models, XGBoost models, things like that.

00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:21.000
Those convert just fine.

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:25.000
But let's say you want to use a model that has some element of recursivity.

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:27.000
Something like k-nearest neighbor.

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:30.000
Well, SQL doesn't have recursivity.

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:32.000
You can't write a recursive function in the SQL.

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:35.000
So unfortunately, you can't use Orbital for that.

00:20:35.000 --> 00:20:39.000
But you can always use Snowflake's Python runtime.

00:20:39.000 --> 00:20:48.000
The other thing to keep in mind is that Orbital does not support and probably won't support something like a neural network model,

00:20:48.000 --> 00:20:51.000
something like a TensorFlow model or a Keras model.

00:20:51.000 --> 00:20:57.000
The reason for that being is those models involve a ton of parallelization with low numeric precision,

00:20:57.000 --> 00:21:02.000
which SQL, quite frankly, these SQL engines are designed for high precision.

00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:03.000
They can parallelize.

00:21:03.000 --> 00:21:13.000
There's nothing mathematically to say that we can't build an Orbital implementation of like, let's say, a Keras model.

00:21:13.000 --> 00:21:19.000
It would be one giant case when statement, but that's mathematically something that we could do.

00:21:19.000 --> 00:21:26.000
Those models are so much better served with GPUs because SQL really doesn't run on GPUs.

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:34.000
That's where something like Snowpark is going to come in a ton of handy because you can have GPUs attached to Snowflake and Snowpark.

00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:39.000
But again, for those cases where I'm sure a lot of us are doing a ton of them all the time,

00:21:39.000 --> 00:21:45.000
where we're building models, building a logistic regression, building a tree based model,

00:21:45.000 --> 00:21:52.000
those take up, those deliver so much value to our customers, to our stakeholders,

00:21:52.000 --> 00:21:57.000
that being able to convert those into SQL, being able to deploy those onto Snowflake effortlessly,

00:21:57.000 --> 00:22:03.000
being able to iterate as fast as I just showed you is going to be a huge step change in your capabilities.

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:06.000
You're going to be able to deploy models faster. Your models are going to run faster.

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:14.000
They're going to run more cheaply and it's just going to make your life that much easier.

00:22:14.000 --> 00:22:22.000
And with that, that's all I've got. So please, I'm super excited to hear your questions and I'll see you in the discussion room.

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:23.000
Thanks, everyone.

